Tokyo here we come! 🇯🇵✨

DAY 1 IN TOKYO🇯🇵 here’s what we did 👇

🐟woke up at 4:30 bc jet lag and went to the Toyosu fish auction. Enjoyed a nice tuna sushi sampler for breakfast! Def recommend doing this the first day if you’re jet lagged. Toyosu or Tsujiki fish markets are highly recommended even though you have to watch from afar due to Covid restrictions. Took the train to shibuya after which took an hour but the day was so young it didn’t matter!

☕️ Starbucks at the famous Shibuya intersection. Had to try their Sakura menu bc i geek out over fast food abroad! Then we walked around Shibuya and checked out Don Julio, a store which has literally everything and is super cool to browse

🌸 from Shibuya we walked through Yoyogi park to head to Harajuku. A few trees were in early bloom so we got to see the gorgeous plum* blossoms! We also did a Kit Kat tasting here which is coming soon and went to the Meji Shrine 

🌭 walked through Harajuku and saw all the trendy fashion/food options! Seb wanted to try these fried potatoes and cheese on a stick at Long Longer Longest. I don’t recommend going out of your way to go there but it was super fun to try bc we passed it!

🍳 tried some 7/11 items including the egg salad sandwich. Def try that when you’re over here! So rich from Kewpie mayo and lots of egg yolks

🥃 after a nap we got cocktails at @palacehoteltokyo’s bar and whether you stay here or not, I definitely recommend for some high end drinks and a wonderful experience. The bartender let us enjoy some local citrus juices as well bc we were geeking out! 

🍣 15 course meal at @sushiishiyama which was INCREDIBLE. I’ll be posting everything we had in my next post! We tried seafood and parts of fish I have never even heard of or thought to try. High end meal 10/10 recommend! The chef is young and takes his craft very seriously

OMAKASE DINNER 🍣 at @sushiishiyama ✨ this was a 15 course high end sushi omakase that we went to on our first night. I can only fit 10 photos here so trying to do a roundup of some highlights! 🍱The chef is young and very serious about his craft. We tried seafood/parts of fish that we didn’t even know existed. Of course, we had tuna and toro which was a major highlight, but we also tried  delicacies like cod sperm, monkfish liver, young sweet shrimp (shiro evil), blood clam, hairy crab (Chinese mitten crab,) squid eggs wrapped in squid meat, scallop liver, engawa (a muscle in flounder,) stonefish and baby eels.

The meal started with sashimi and ended with nigiri and a hand roll if you had room (which I shockingly didn’t.) The chef asks if you’re satisfied before closing out the meal. 

🍣 Some “classics” (by classics I mean what we are aware of in America) we had were lean tuna, medium fatty tuna, fatty tuna, amberjack, scallop (which wasn’t as sweet as the ones we have back in the US,) uni which was the best uni I’ve ever had, eel, sardine, squid, and ebi which was sweet and more intense than the sweet shrimp I’ve had in the US.

👨‍🍳 Also for a disclaimer, the staff said it was okay for me to film and photograph. Before the meal, you get a list of instructions that tell you things you can and can’t do. ie: no photos without asking, no wearing perfume, no putting your phone on the counter and no being late.  It’s very important to be early or on time for all meals in Japan.

🍶For drinks we tried 2 different types of sake throughout the meal. One dry and one sweeter - we asked for the chefs recommendations and it paired beautifully. All around such an elegant meal. We asked the concierge at our hotel to make the reservation and I recommend doing that for any higher end restaurants! With sake it was around $250 per person, which was one of our splurge meals.

TOKYO DAY 2 ITINERARY👇

This was a Sunday for us and these spots were open!

🦑 Started off the day going to Yanaka Ginza, which is known as the old town district with a shopping st that’s been around since the 1950’s. The area has lots of historical charm and some cool food vendors. We tried a lot of things but narrowed the 2 “must haves” to be the Takoyaki from Yanaka Tokobo and the Ikasen from Ikayaki Yakiya 🦑 Ikayaki is a squid pancake and the most popular Ikasen from this spot has the Ikayaki sandwiches between two shrimp crackers with cheese. That was my favorite!

🌳 From there we took a walk to Ueno park where we randomly stumbled upon a Samurai festival. We also went to the zoo which isn’t worth it IMO. 

🏬 We kept walking through the park until we got to Ameyoko shopping st which was popping off - lots of food vendors and little shops. I will say we LOVE walking (shoutout to Hoka shoes for feeling like a cloud) but you can also take a train and skip going to the park all together. I loved this market because it had so much character and felt more local than other markets we had been to. There’s also supposed to be an underground shopping area that we couldn’t find but we didn’t care lol. 

🍓 At the market I tried some Japanese candies strawberries and omg you HAVE to try strawberries when you’re here. There are over 100 varieties and they’re extremely sweet like candy. The grapes are also incredible. 

🎮 we kept walking and ended up in Akihabara which is known for having lots of shops and electronic stores. We found an arcade called GIGO 3 and decided to go bc why not - we were very humbled that all the games we grew up with were in the “retro” section of the 6 floor arcade. Super random fun detour 😆 also went to Yodobashi electronic store and finally bought a Nintendo switch 🤣 I had to. If you want to get one make sure you bring your passport and you can avoid tax. I had no idea so had to eat the 10% tax 🤷‍♀️ 

🍖 Finally for dinner we ended up getting a Yakitori omakase at a hidden spot in a basement in the Akasaka area - we went by train. I can’t find the name of it but def recommend grabbing a yakitori meal while you’re here!

TOKYO DAY 3 ITINERARY👇

🪷 started the day by going to Asakusa to check out the oldest Buddhist temple in Tokyo, Senso-Ji. It was absolutely beautiful and highly recommend coming to the temple and exploring the shopping streets in Asakusa!

🍡while we were in Asakusa we went on a major food crawl bc duh, culinary research of course !! Some highlights were 1) Taiyaki (fish shaped pastry with a filling) traditionally it’s red bean  but we got red bean and custard)  2) Kibi dango sweet millet dumplings coated in kibi grain flour which had a sweet/umami soy flavor and a nutty element like peanut butter. Delicious!

🍜 we also tried a Hokkaido style miso ramen which was simple and decadent. The restaurant was called Hokkaidou and was low key and local. I recommend getting ramen here or anywhere in Tokyo!!! So rich and delicious! 

🥞 final Asakusa stop was a pancake restaurant called Benitsuru. I didn’t realize it was super trendy, and we went bc it was in the area we were exploring that day. We had fluffy soufflé honey butter pancakes with strawberries. 

🐠 we took a long walk to the Tsujiki fish market which was super crowded and cool to see. There are tons of seafood vendors and restaurants to enjoy seafood! You can go to this one at 5am but I’m glad we went to Toyosu for the auction/breakfast on the first day and then went to this one for a fun daytime activity. Definitely recommend going here!

🖼️ we walked to Toyosu to go to Team Labs, which is an experiential art museum. Super cool if u like that kind of stuff! You have to reserve in advance and the entire experience is about an hour

🥩 for dinner we went to a teppanyaki restaurant and I definitely recommend trying teppanyaki while in Japan (it’s a post world war 2 style of cooking where the chef uses an iron griddle to prepare food in front of you— not hibachi but similar!) the Kobe beef we had was a 10/10 😍😍😍

TOKYO DAY 4 ITINERARY 👇 this was our bougie relaxation day so we didn’t do much except eat, walk and relax! 😅 we have a relaxation day in both the Kyoto and Tokyo parts of the trip so we don’t get too tired from all the running around.

☕️ In the morning we had breakfast at our hotel then made the trip to Roppongi Hills - a very affluent section of the city with a high end shopping mall. I personally wouldn’t put it on a “must see” list but we went there for lunch so it was cool to see.

🍣 went to the famous Sukiyabashi Jiro’s second location (entire recap video coming soon.) We had lunch and it was a lot of sushi packed into a 30 minute window. It was pricy at $160 per person. The sushi absolutely lived up to the hype, but I wasn’t a fan of the expedited pace that made it feel very transactional. I understand fast omakase lunches are part of Tokyo culture but usually the price is less than the $160 per person for lunch and should fall around $100. If you want to try some epic sushi, I definitely recommend it tho! Maybe you can ask for a slower pace. 

🧖‍♀️ after lunch we went back to the hotel to use the pool and hot tub. If you stay at the palace, it’s a must! Gooooorgeous views and such a nice facility. Highly recommend this hotel in general. We booked a year in advance and were able to secure a decent rate. 

🥂 finished our Tokyo part of the trip with an epic bougie meal at the 2 Michelin star restaurant Narisawa. I’ll be posting a full video about the experience soon! This is extreme high level fine dining (if you’ve seen The Menu on hbo, it gives a similar vibe with the culinary talent but with nice people and not scary lol— this is supposed to be a compliment.) We did the dinner with a sake pairing and had BLOWFISH for the first time, and luckily survived! 😁 Definitely recommend for special occasions or if you want to get a taste for some extra fine dining in Tokyo. 

👋 in the morning we said our goodbyes and headed to Kyoto for a much more zen part of the trip! Can’t wait to share more about our time here!!!!!
really enjoying the private onsen experience - so zen and peaceful thanks to Sebastian!

KYOTO DAY 1 ITINERARY👇

🏨 Checked into the hyatt regency which wasn’t my favorite out of all the hotels we stayed at but it was solid 

🧡Walked to the Kiyomizu-dera Temple and then the Higashiyama district which is full of beautiful traditional architecture and lots of food shops. Very touristy and crowded but super cool to see!

🍡Also walked to Sannen-zaka and Ninnen-zaka which are old shopping streets that are beautiful as well

🍱Walked back to the hotel and got ready for dinner at Kodaji Ju Gyuen which was our FAVE dinner of Kyoto! So romantic and a private dining experience in a traditional 120 year old home. You sit at a traditional dining table on the floor and enjoy a Kaseiki style meal ( traditional Japanese cuisine in which a series of very small, seasonal dishes are prepared.) I will say, for Americans, trying a traditional Kaiseki meal might come as a shock because there is a lot of whole fish involved. You eat every part of the fish, head to tail including the bones. There are also some flavor profiles that are pickled and briny that we don’t have every day, so keep an open mind if you try one of these dinners! 

🍶I will have a full video of this experience coming but I highly recommend this restaurant to get an elevated taste of traditional Japanese food. We went to 2 other Michelin star spots and this was by far our favorite due to all the factors: ambiance/food/drink. We got the sake pairing and it was next level— we learned that we love traditional Kyoto style sake which has a slight effervescence to

KYOTO DAY 2 (NARA DAY TRIP) 👇

🦌 For our second day in Kyoto we decided to explore another city called Nara. It’s a 30 min train ride away and there’s a beautiful park, temples and DEER everywhere. Yes deer in the streets. They be vibing. This was such a fun day trip to break up all the major urban vibes and I recommend it for anyone who wants to go on a nice long walk to explore the gorgeous Nara Park and see the deer, which literally come up to you. I saw as many deer there as I see squirrels in Philly! Thought it was so cool. 

🌁Other than enjoying a nature moment and wandering through the park, we also wandered around the small city streets. There’s markets here where you can grab food and lots of restaurants to enjoy. 

🍜We went for udon dipping noodles, which you eat and dip into a broth that is served on the side. They were deliiiiiish and 10/10 recommend. Also recommend trying mochi here! There’s a really popular stand where they make it by hand and are smacking it (you may have seen the viral TikTok about that) but def check that out too!

😴We stayed in Nara for a few hours and then came back to chill and have a room service dinner. Our next day was also a chill day too bc we need to balance all the hectic with some zen
I’m now an @allnipponairways fan for LIIIIFE. We booked these with our points a full year in advance to get a good rate. ✈️ #flyana

KYOTO DAY 3 (relaxation chill day) 👇

🧖‍♀️ I’ve always wanted to try a Japanese onsen experience and while this isn’t exactly that (onsen is a naturally occurring hotspring) it was a wonderful spa day with a thermal spring experience. I booked us the TOKI experience at the Hotel the Mitsui in Kyoto. It’s a 90 minute massage/facial combo designed by an acupuncturist. Before our treatment, we had an hour to use the hotel’s thermal spring, which we luckily had all to ourselves. This was suchhhh a nice relaxing break to the trip and def recommend for a day of luxury. 

☄️After that, we walked around and stumbled upon a Pokémon store LOL bc I’m such a nerd and just haaaaad to go and buy Nintendo switch games 💀 

🍬 Then we went to Teramachi to walk around and grab a snack (went back the next day for a proper food tour.) Def recommend going to Teramachi and Nishiki market to walk around! 

🎣 For dinner we went to a 1 Michelin star spot called Jiki Miyazawa. It is a traditional Kaiseki style dining spot. The chef was excellent and was so thoughtful to explain locally sourced seafood/meat/vegetables to us. He even let us try a very traditional kind of sake that hasn’t been filtered which was so cool. I will say (respectfully) it wasn’t my favorite meal of the trip and I think this is because a lot of traditional Japanese dishes that include whole fish/briny ingredients aren’t my favorite flavor profiles. I think my opinion is solely based on my preference in flavors and that the chef and his team did an *amazing* job with all the dishes he gave us. So, if you’re up for an adventure and want to try some really traditional different flavor profiles than what we are used to in the US, def give this place a shot! Also, it’s super important to know that it’s extremely rude not to finish your meal when going out to eat in Japan. We didn’t love some dishes but ate everything at every meal! Final thought here is that every kaiseki restaurant uses ingredients in season and the menus consistently change, so if you go the menu could be completely different.
Hot girls don’t gate keep saving money on makeup 💄 shade is 17 cool but there are other shades you can go with

KYOTO DAY 4 (food tour and a nature moment) 🍤👇

We went back to Teramachi and Nishiki market for a *proper* tasting tour. Sooooo many great dishes and my 3 faves were:

🦀 1) crab tempura- you MUST try it, so tender/sweet/salty/crunchy. There’s a huge tempura street food scene here. Lots of tempura on sticks which I love. 

🍡 2) daifuku strawberry mochi - daifuku is a term for stuffed mochi and this one was stuffed with a sweet red bean purée and a Japanese strawberry. Dooooo not sleep on these! Enjoy all the daifuku while you’re in Japan and alllll the strawberries too bc they’re truly epic. So sweet like candy. 

🥚3) dashimiki tamago sandwich - i know everyone raves about the egg salad sandwiches here (which are fantastic) but this also deserves some HYPE! Dashimiki Tamago is a Japanese rolled omelet and the eggs are cooked in broth for extra flavor. It’s so fluffy and airy. The sandwich had a little mayo (which I thought had a little spice in it) and was on soft white bread. If you don’t like eggs obviously don’t eat this lol but it was really good and I was a fan! 

🍰 4) black sesame Mont Blanc cake - ok this is traditionally a French dessert but it’s everywhere in Kyoto with Japanese flavor spins so I had to try. If you’re wondering what it is, it’s a cake with custard covered in a chestnut purée. They serve it over mochi skewers too (which I obviously tried) but the winner for me was the black sesame Mont Blanc cake. They mixed black sesame in with the cake and the chestnut purée and it was a nutty, sweet, rich contrast to vanilla custard in the middle. Ugh SO DIVINE. 

🐒We spent the second half of the day going to Arishayama on the outskirts of Kyoto. That’s where I found the Mont Blanc cake btw. We took the train and it was an easy 20 minutes that was welllll worth it. 100000% recommend going here for half a day. We first hiked up a mountain to see monkeys, which I didn’t think would be worth it but it was just for the view (and the monkeys.) 🎍Then, we went to Sagano bamboo way, which was GORGEOUS. It’s only one road which was crowded but worth it to see. Arishayama is a must see and I highly recommend 💯

OSAKA DAY 1 👇 

We only had 2 days in Osaka and there’s so much more I’d like to do, but here’s our itinerary! Also, I took a break from eating st food for this part of the trip bc i was so full 🤪 but recommendations below!

🏙️ We stayed at the Intercontinental which was GOOOOORG and I highly recommend. 💯 

🦑Went to the Dotonbori district and the Shinaibashisuji shopping streets. This is WILD. Like Times Square but with giant moving seafood statues everywhere. There’s lots of tempura, takoyaki (def recommend getting it here,) okonomiyaki (another Osaka staple!), skewers, Kobe and wagyu beef. Def recommend doing a food crawl here!!!! We had a big dinner this night so we actually skipped our food crawl since we had tried a lot of these types of dishes in Tokyo and saved space for dinner. I 100000% recommend getting all the dishes listed above when you go. 

🥂Now speaking of our dinner, we had the most *epic* meal of the trip at Hajime, a 3 Michelin star restaurant with a French influenced Japanese menu (see last slide with sound on for a great example of why Seb and I are so embarrassing in nice places.) My GOD the chef and his team are ARTISTS!!!! This was such a wild experience and I will be featuring it on Skyler’s Splurge Eats. Financially, it was a splurge, but it was one of those meals I will never forget and those memories are priceless. It was also extremely inspirational in terms of the culinary arts. I love fine dining because the creativity is unmatched. At this place there was a lot of science behind some of the dishes (think: smoky sea water around a plate of oysters or cheese “powder” that turns to air in your mouth.) Also, I will say this was a very long meal so if you book a reservation, make it early! It was 4-5 hours!

an nyc moment ❤️ went to 2 splurge restaurants on a whim: American cut in Tribeca and Sushi Seki on the UES. #SkylersSplurgeEats HONEST OPINION👇

🥩 American cut is super flashy (it’s a steakhouse so no surprise) and it’s pricy, we had lots of fun but do I think it’s worth the price? No bc our Tomahawk steak didn’t taste dry aged and it was supposed to be for  30 days 😬 this is just my opinion, respectfully! The service was great and so was the vibe! Also everything else was really good (got the chopped salad and shrimp cocktail as well.) We just went all out on the steak, which was delicious but not the dry age I was expecting for the price ya know?

🍣 Sushi Seki omakase is $150 per person and after having gone to Japan, I can confirm this spot is extremely legit! It’s no secret — sushi Seki is a fave in NYC for takeout, sit down and omakase. The fish selection was on par with what we had in Japan with the addition of flavorful sauces and some American spins (ie: salmon nigiri with a seared tomato on top, which was so unreal and unexpected)

RESTAURANT RECAP ✨ Spice Finch, Center City Philly 📍 this is a Mediterranean spot that I’ve been to twice and really liked it both times! I think it’s worth the 💰

Great for date night and also great for a double date or girls night. Suuuuuper cute bar and great cocktails (and mocktails) too. Noticed lots of vibrant fresh herbs with each dish so if you’re not an herb/spice person maybe skip this one! Our fave orders? Listing them👇

🥙trio of spreads- great starter with these crispy deep fried BBQ like pita chips.  Could eat tons of those. 

🍗Duck wings (almost typo’ed dick wings which would have been traumatic lol): looooved these in a sticky, sweet pomegranate BBQ glaze. Paired with crispy chickpeas and a Turkish hummus. 

🍤 Peri peri shrimp - shrimp served with lots of fresh herbs, harissa, preserved lemon, garlic and a flatbread. Loved these just wish there were more 😍

🍖Chili chicken kebab - this was a WOW entree for us. Juicy chicken thighs with a sesame yogurt and tons of fresh herbs. Loved the savory/nutty/tangy/bright/vibrant contrast to this dish. Also the hot chicken with the cool yogurt sauce 😍

🥩 Moroccan steak frites - this was savory, spiced and beautifully cooked! The kebab was more my vibe but loved this too. 

🍦 warm tahini brownie with vanilla ice cream and halva. Such a sexy luscious dessert. 

Other dishes I’ve tried that were good and fun but not my absolute fave like the ones above 

🫕 Baked cheese - i know i know, obviously this is gonna be delicious but I think if you’re here for creativity and major flavors, this is something that you can probably find somewhere else. 

Lamb shank - this is their classic entree for two which was really good but not my fave after trying the chicken kebab and steak frites!

SKYLER’S SPLURGE EATS 💰Vernick Fish in Center City 📍 followed by a cocktail at JG Skyhigh (which is right upstairs!) this was a fun swanky date night. Great vibes and service at Vernick Fish and the food was delish! I’d say the cuisine is obviously seafood but with a fusion element to it — lots of Asian spins, some Latin American influence and also seasonal local ingredients. 

I’m not sure how often the menu changes but here are the most outstanding dishes we tried: 

MUST ORDER: Snapper ceviche (slide 2) crispy octopus (slide 5) and the swordfish katsu (slide 7)

Also enjoyed the seared scallops (they were cooked perfectly, I just wasn’t 100% vibing with the accompaniments on the plate which I think could have been more contrasting in flavor but that’s a personal opinion!) sea bream crudo and salmon crudo but they were a 9/10 while we found those 👆 to be a 10/10. You can’t really lose!

🍸 For drinks I recommend getting cocktails because the wine list is pretty limited. 

Also, go to dinner early and snag an early seat at JG sky high for an after dinner cocktail. GORGEOUS space and great drinks 🍺

My girl @beckerinjectorbrooke’s new skin boosting facial is my new obsession. No downtime and gorgeous glowing skin😍 I have NO face makeup on at the end of this video, just my brows!!!! It’s insane 

🩸 so here’s how it works: she draws your blood and spins the PRF (which I’ve gotten injected under my eyes, check my previous reel!) and then she adds Botox to the solution. She uses these tiny gold needles to infuse the PRF/Botox into the skin— the Botox minimizes the pores (it’s not affecting any muscles so it’s not like Botox injections) and then the PRF hydrates and repairs the skin. 

I’m a huuuuuge fan of these PRF treatments because they come from your own body and repair the skin. I feel revived after this one and wanna do this before big shoots or events! ✨ #prf #prfskin #aquagold

Went to Tulip pasta and wine bar a few weeks ago and here are my thoughts! Super cute vibe and great for people who want to enjoy some cool pasta dishes! Honest thoughts 👇

🍝 theyre *really* good at making homemade pasta (all the pastas had unreal texture and beautiful presentation!) but some of their dishes were a little too out of the box for me personally, and I consider myself very out of the box. For example, Meyer lemon tagliatelle with tuna tartare. Not a combo I’d think of but was willing to try! Texture of the pasta was supreme but in terms of flavor it wasn’t all there and didn’t all mesh (IMO.) It was good but not Seb and I‘s personal favorite. I loved the spaghetti with ramps - the pasta kind of reminded me of a buckwheat noodle since it was made with an einkorn flour. It was funky and I’d prefer a regular pasta but I did enjoy the creativity! I also had an agnolotti which I don’t see on their current menu. This was my favorite of the night with sweet/savory/salty/meaty flavors : there was rhubarb, brown butter, Parmesan and I think it was beef (I forget though I’m sorry!!!)

🥖 LOVED the house made stracciatella with delicata caponata. Unreal 

✨If I go back I’d definitely try the rigatoni with spicy lamb sausage and the linguine with mussels too to add a more traditional element to our dining experience 

🍷 not gonna lie, I was a little bummed about the wine list (only bc they call themselves a wine bar and I was excited about a good selection) bc it was only PA wines. But I had an open mind because never judge a wine until you have it!! Sadly the Riesling we had was very flat and not vibrant (which means the bottle was opened a day or two before and probably not stored correctly.) I totally get liquor restrictions in Philly are *horrendous* and this is a new spot so they’re probably figuring out the kinks. But I do think calling this place a wine bar is a bit of a stretch! IMO, come here for dinner then get cocktails at Four Humors Distilling co after.
so much fun celebrating @nickirmarie and @mfrancolino. Congrats!! 👰‍♀️🤵‍♂️ ❤️

First night in Mexico City! 🇲🇽 Went to Maximo Bistrot for a tasting menu dinner and everything was delicious 🥂Lots of food though (even for us!) so come starving and hangry lol would say this place is def worth the hype tho if you want a fusion type of restaurant and not 100% authentic Mexican cuisine. ✨

high end dining in CDMX🇲🇽 #SkylersSplurgeEats tried out Quintonil last night and loved it! It’s a tasting menu so you’re locked in to what they’re serving (pending any dietary restrictions that you give in advance) 

🐜 insects are a common part of Mexican cuisine and there’s no shortage on the menu here. We tried multiple insects that were incorporated into various parts of the menu including my favorite, escamoles, which are actually ant eggs. I’ve heard this is like Mexican caviar. Really delicious! 

here’s the menu we had: 

1. Light salad - spin on a Caesar 
2. Cantaloupe and tomato salad with brown butter

In my humble opinion, the winner for best high end restaurant in CDMX goes to Pujol! 🇲🇽 #SkylersSplurgeEats we tried 3 of the nicest spots in the city, and this one was our favorite meal. ✨ The other two we went to were Quintonil and Maximo (see my other posts!), so in my opinion, if you had to choose one, this is it! Quintonil was the most expensive so I’m surprised it didn’t deliver more than Pujol. 😅 also want to note that we went here for lunch, so the dinner menu is probably different. They have great cocktails and non alcoholic drinks as well as an impressive wine list 🍷 posted these in reverse order bc the desserts were just so beautiful!❤️ my fave dishes were the chicken chicharron with abalone and lime zest, the scallop ceviche and the corn and blueberry dessert. All were delicious though and this was def the most well balanced tasting menu we enjoyed
